Learning Git branching, forking, push, pull, and merge using Git Bash is simple if you follow clear steps.

First, configure Git on your system using git config 
--global user.name "Your Name" and git config 
--global user.email "your@email.com". 
This sets your identity for commits. To start working on a project, 
use git clone <repository-url> 
to download it from GitHub to your local machine, then move into the project folder using cd folder-name. You can check your current project status anytime with git status.

To save changes, first stage files using git add . (which selects all changes), then create a snapshot using 
git commit -m "message"
If you want to work on a new feature without affecting the main code, create a branch using 
git checkout -b branch-name. This creates and switches to a new branch. You can see all branches using git branch, and switch between them using git checkout branch-name.

When your work is ready, upload it to GitHub using 
git push origin branch-name. 
If you want to get the latest updates from the remote repository, use 
git pull origin branch-name. To combine branches, first switch to the main branch using git checkout main, then merge another branch into it using 
git merge branch-name. If a merge conflict appears, open the file, fix the issue manually, then 
run git add . and 
git commit -m "Fixed conflict".

Forking is done on GitHub’s website by clicking the Fork button, which creates a copy of someone else’s repository in your account. After forking, you clone your fork and work on it normally. In summary: clone downloads a project, add and commit save changes, branch creates a new working line, push uploads changes, pull downloads updates, merge combines branches, and fork copies a repository to your account.
